<subSubSection id="C3176560FF86FFE81FC8FB9BFB234EF5" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BB236EBFF86FFE81FC8FB9BFB234EF5" blockId="16.[151,1436,1114,1247]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Diagnosis—Pedicel with very short bristles, pterostigma usually present. Distal tibial spines often present on front and mid tibiae. Tergite 1 with lateral fan of setae absent or minute, tergite 6 often with lateral protuberances, membranous area of ST8 usually absent, phallus trifid, ejaculatory apodeme usually funnel- shaped or three-sided, very large, with a swollen basal rosette. For more details see 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9C4B1AFF86FFE81C1DFB07FB2F4EF5" author="Skevington and Yeates" box="[834,1174,1222,1246]" firstAuthor="Skevington" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="421 - 452" refId="ref90034" refString="Skevington, J. H. &amp; Yeates, D. K. (2001) Phylogenetic classification of Eudorylini (Diptera: Pipunculidae). Systematic Entomology, 26, 421 - 452." type="journal article" year="2001">Skevington and Yeates (2001)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
